===Education===
According to the [[UN]], Costa Rica's literacy rate stands at 95.8%,&lt;ref&gt;http://hdr.undp.org/en/media/HDI_2008_EN_Tables.pdf&lt;/ref&gt; the fifth highest among [[Latin America|Latin American Countries]]. Costa Rica's [[Education Index]] in 2006 was 0.882; higher than that of richer countries, such as [[Singapore]] and [[Mexico]]. However Costa Rica's gross enrolment ratio is only 73.0%, smaller than that of the neighbors countries of [[El Salvador]] and [[Honduras]].&lt;ref&gt;http://hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/country_fact_sheets/cty_fs_CRI.html&lt;/ref&gt;

All students must complete [[Primary School]] and [[Secondary School]], between 6 and 15 years. But some students drop out because they must work to help support their families. In 2007 there were 536,436 pupils enrolled in 3,771 primary schools and 377,900 students attended public and private secondary schools.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Costa Rica - MSN Encarta &lt;!-- BOT GENERATED TITLE --&gt;|url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761572479_3/Costa_Rica.html|work=|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kwbHIv21|archivedate=2009-10-31|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Costa Rica's main [[Universities of Costa Rica|Universities]] are the [[University of Costa Rica]], in [[San Jose, Costa Rica|San Jose]] and the [[National University of Costa Rica]], in [[Heredia, Costa Rica|Heredia]]. Costa Rica also has several [[Private Universities]].

===Emigration and immigration===
Costa Rica's emigration is among the smallest in the [[Caribbean Basin]]. About 3% of the country's people live in another country as immigrants. The main destination countries are the [[United States]], [[Spain]], [[Mexico]] and other [[Central America|Central American Countries]]. In 2005, there were 127,061 Costa Ricans living in another country as immigrants. [[Remittance]]s were $513,000,000 in 2006 and they represented 2.3% of the country's GDP.

Costa Rica's immigration is among the largest in the [[Caribbean Basin]]. Immigrants in Costa Rica represent about 10.2% of the Costa Rican population. The main countries of origin are [[Nicaragua]], [[Colombia]] and [[El Salvador]]. In 2005, there were 440,957 people in the country living as immigrants. Outward Remittances were $246,000,000 in 2006.

