===Foreign Relations===
{{Main|Foreign relations of Croatia}}
{{See also|Accession of Croatia to the European Union|International rankings of Croatia}}

Croatia applied to become a [[Member State of the European Union|member of the]] [[European Union]] (EU) in 2003 and gained candidate status in 2004. Croatia is expected to become an EU state in the second half of 2011. Its accession was previously blocked by [[Slovenia]] due to [[Slovenia's blockade of Croatia's EU accession|a maritime dispute]].

==Economy==
{{Main|Economy of Croatia}}
{{See also|List of companies of Croatia|Tourism in Croatia}}
[[File:Bol na Bracu - Zlatni rat.jpg|thumb|[[Zlatni Rat]] beach on the island of [[Brač]]. [[Tourism]] accounts for around 20% of [[GDP]]]]

[[Privatization]] and the drive toward a [[market economy]] had barely begun under the new Croatian Government when war broke out in 1991. As a result of the war, the economic infrastructure sustained massive damage, particularly the revenue-rich tourism industry.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt; From 1989 to 1993, GDP fell 40.5%.&lt;ref name=DOS&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/3166.htm|title=Background Note: Croatia|publisher=U.S. Department of state|accessdate=2008-12-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; With the end of the war in 1995, [[tourism]] and Croatia's economy recovered moderately.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt; However, [[Political corruption|corruption]], [[cronyism]], and a general lack of [[Transparency (behavior)|transparency]] stymied meaningful economic reform, as well as much-needed [[Foreign direct investment|foreign investment]].&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt;

Croatia's economy turned the corner in 2000 as tourism rebounded.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt; The economy expanded in 2002, stimulated by a credit boom led by newly privatized and foreign-capitalized banks, some capital investment, most importantly road construction, further growth in tourism, and gains by small and medium-sized private enterprises.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt;

Croatia has a [[High income economy|high-income]] market economy.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/DATASTATISTICS/0,,contentMDK:20421402~pagePK:64133150~piPK:64133175~theSitePK:239419,00.html#High_income |title=World Bank Country Classifications 2008 |publisher=Web.worldbank.org |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[International Monetary Fund]] data shows that Croatian [[nominal GDP]] stood at $69.357&amp;nbsp;billion, or $15,633 per capita,&lt;ref name=imf2/&gt; at the same time in 2008 [[purchasing power parity]] [[GDP]] was $82.407&amp;nbsp;billion or $18,575 per capita.&lt;ref name=imf2/&gt;

[[File:Palaca Jadran Jadrolinija Rijeka 4408.jpg|thumb|[[Jadrolinija]] (sea [[shipping]] company) headquarters building in [[Rijeka]].]]
[[File:Zagreb tram (21).jpg|thumb|A [[CROTRAM|Croatian made]] [[tram]].]]

According to [[Eurostat]] data, Croatian PPS GDP per capita stood at 63.2 percent of the EU average in 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_PUBLIC/2-25062009-BP/EN/2-25062009-BP-EN.PDF|title=GDP per capita in PPS|publisher=Eurostat|accessdate=2009-06-25}}&lt;/ref&gt; Real GDP growth in 2007 was 6.0 per cent.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page?_pageid=1996,39140985&amp;_dad=portal&amp;_schema=PORTAL&amp;screen=detailref&amp;language=en&amp;product=STRIND_ECOBAC&amp;root=STRIND_ECOBAC/ecobac/eb012|title=Real GDP growth rate|publisher=Eurostat|accessdate=2008-05-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; and at the same time average gross salary of a Croatian worker during the first nine months of 2008 was 7,161 kuna ([[US$]] 1,530) per month&lt;ref name=salary7161&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.suvremena.hr/9044.aspx|title=Plaće nominalno veće, ali realno u padu|accessdate=2008-11-21|date=2008-11-06|work=Suvremena.hr|language=Croatian}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2007, the [[International Labour Organization]]-defined [[unemployment]] rate stood at 9.1 per cent, after falling steadily from 14.7 percent in 2002.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/portal/page?_pageid=1996,39140985&amp;_dad=portal&amp;_schema=PORTAL&amp;screen=detailref&amp;language=en&amp;product=STRIND_EMPLOI&amp;root=STRIND_EMPLOI/emploi/em071|title=Unemployment rate – total|publisher=Eurostat|accessdate=2008-03-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; The registered unemployment rate is higher, though, standing at 13.7 percent in December 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hnb.hr/publikac/bilten/arhiv/bilten-134/ebilt134.pdf?tsfsg=b65a34caa3a314c04e2cba8c626caa79|title=Bulletin 134|publisher=Croatian National Bank|date=February 2008|accessdate=2008-03-22}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2009, economic output was dominated by the service sector which accounted for 73,6% percent of GDP, followed by the [[industrial sector]] with 20,5% and [[agriculture]] accounting for 5,9% of GDP.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www2.hgk.hr/en/pdf/croatia_bussines_partner_2009.pdf|title=Croatian Chamber of Economy Brochure for year 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;
According to 2004 data, 2.7
percent of the workforce were employed in agriculture, 32.8 percent by
industry and 64.5 in services.&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2007/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=27&amp;pr.y=10&amp;sy=2004&amp;ey=2008&amp;scsm=1&amp;ssd=1&amp;sort=country&amp;ds=.&amp;br=1&amp;c=960&amp;s=NGDPD%2CNGDPDPC%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC%2CPPPSH%2CPPPEX%2CLP&amp;grp=0&amp;a=
|title=World Economic Outlook Database|publisher=International
Monetary Fund|date=October 2007|accessdate=2008-03-09}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The industrial sector is dominated by shipbuilding, food processing, pharmaceuticals, information technology, biochemical and timber industry. [[Tourism]] is a notable source of income during the summers, with over 11&amp;nbsp;million foreign tourists in 2008 generating a revenue of €8&amp;nbsp;billion.&lt;ref name=UNWTO&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.unwto.org/facts/eng/pdf/barometer/UNWTO_Barom07_3_en.pdf|title=UNWTO World Tourism Barometer|date=October 2007|accessdate=2008-04-23}}&lt;/ref&gt; Croatia is ranked as the 18th most popular tourist destination in the world.&lt;ref name=UNWTO/&gt; In 2008 Croatia exported goods to the value of $14.4&amp;nbsp;billion ([[Free On Board|FOB]]) ($26.4&amp;nbsp;billion including service exports).&lt;ref name=UNWTO/&gt;

The Croatian state still controls a significant part of the economy, with government expenditure accounting for as much as 40% of GDP.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt; Some large, state-owned industries, such as the country's shipyards, continue to rely on government subsidies but with EU membership looming, Croatia is forced to restructure debt ridden shipyards as it is a prerequisites for Croatia before it joins the EU. Subsidies for loss making industries also reduce needed investments in to education and technology needed to ensure the economy's long-term competitiveness.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt;

Of particular concern is the backlogged [[judiciary]] system, combined with inefficient [[public administration]], especially issues of land ownership and corruption. Another main problem includes the large and growing national debt which has reached over 34&amp;nbsp;billion euro or 89.1 per cent of the nations gross domestic product.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/business/news/article_1411971.php/ANALYSIS_Despite_debt_Croatia_&amp;quotnot_under_financial_collapse_threat%22 |title=Analysis: Despite debt, Croatia &quot;not under financial collapse threat&quot; |publisher=Monstersandcritics.com |date=2008-06-18 |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; Because of these problems, studies show that the population of Croatia generally has negative expectations of the country's economic future.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.balkan-monitor.eu/files/BalkanMonitor-2008_Summary_of_Findings.pdf |title=Gallup Balkan monitor:2008 Summary of findings |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Croatia has so far weathered the global financial crisis reasonably well, but faces significant challenges in 2010 largely due to Croatia's external imbalances and high [[External debt|foreign debt]], which in longer term presents problems for Croatian financial sector due to higher cost of borrowing to cover current account deficit.&lt;ref name=DOS/&gt;

The country has been preparing for membership in the [[European Union]], its most important [[international trade|trading partner]]. In February 2005, the [[Stabilisation and Association Process|Stabilisation and Association Agreement]] with the [[European Union|EU]] officially came into force and by the end of 2009 Croatia has closed 17 EU accessions chapters, with remaining 16 to be completed by the end of first half of 2010. Croatia is expected to join the [[EU]] sometimes in 2011 or January first 2012 together with [[Iceland]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7860078.stm |title=Iceland 'could join EU by 2011' |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-01-30 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{-}}

===Transport===
{{Main|Transport in Croatia}}
[[File:C Vrbovsko A6 0509.jpg|thumb|[[A6 (Croatia)|A6 motorway]]]]
[[File:Croatian railways tilting and regional.png|thumb|A regional train and tilting train of the Croatian Railways.]]

The highlight of Croatia's recent [[infrastructure]] developments is its rapidly growing [[Motorways in Croatia|motorway network]], of which plans were drawn and work commenced in the 1970s, but was realised only after independence because of the (then) [[SFRY|Yugoslav Government]] plans of road projects of 'national' importance.&lt;ref name=&quot;Autocesta-Kralja-Tomislava&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.matica.hr/HRRevija/revija2004_4_n.nsf/AllWebDocs/Milicic | title= Autocesta Split - Zagreb | trans_title=Autocesta Split - Zagreb | year=2004 | work=Hrvatska revija | author=Jakša Miličić | publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=May 16, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Vjesnik-Haramija&quot;&gt;{{cite news | newspaper = Vjesnik | language = Croatian | url = http://www.vjesnik.hr/Pdf/2004%5C06%5C27%5C09A9.PDF | title = Naša ideja je bila izgraditi ono što samo zvali 'hrvatski križ' | trans_title= Our idea was to build what we called 'Croatian cross' | author= Tihomir Ponoš | format= PDF | date = June 27, 2004 | accessdate= October 7, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1997, at the Third Ministerial Session of the [[International Transport Forum|European Conference of Ministers of Transport]], routes of four [[Pan-European corridors]] were defined running through Croatia, giving extra importance to Croatian road network.&lt;ref name=&quot;Helsinki-1997&quot;&gt;{{cite journal | publisher = [[University of Rijeka|University of Rijeka, Faculty of Maritime Studies]] | url = http://hrcak.srce.hr/file/6570 | title= The integration of the Republic of Croatia into the Pan-European transport corridor network | author= Tanja Poletan Jugović | journal= Pomorstvo | volume= 20 | issue= 1 | pages= 49–65 | date = April 11, 2006 | accessdate= October 14, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Croatia has now over {{convert|1100|km|abbr=off}} of completed motorways connecting Zagreb to most other regions.&lt;ref name=&quot;NN-Motorways2007&quot;&gt;{{cite news | newspaper = [[Narodne Novine]] | language = Croatian | url = http://narodne-novine.nn.hr/clanci/sluzbeni/2007_07_77_2443.html | title = Odluka o razvrstavanju javnih cesta u autoceste | trans_title= Decision on classification of public roads as motorways | date = July 25, 2007 | accessdate= October 18, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;NN-Motorways2009&quot;&gt;{{cite news | newspaper = Narodne Novine | language = Croatian | url = http://narodne-novine.nn.hr/clanci/sluzbeni/2009_01_13_296.html | title = Odluka o izmjenama i dopunama odluke o razvrstavanju javnih cesta u autoceste | trans_title= Decision on amendments and additions to the Decision on classification of public roads as motorways | date = January 30, 2009 | accessdate= October 18, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The best known and the busiest motorways are the [[A1 (Croatia)|A1]], connecting Zagreb to [[Split (city)|Split]] and the [[A3 (Croatia)|A3]], passing east–west through northwest Croatia and [[Slavonia]]. Toll is charged at most sections of the motorways—the most notable exceptions are [[Zagreb bypass]] and Rijeka bypass. There is also a smaller and less known [[Expressways in Croatia|network of expressways]] connecting to the motorways. The most heavily used ones are the [[A8 (Croatia)|B8]], connecting the [[A7 (Croatia)|A7]] near Rijeka to the [[A9 (Croatia)|A9]] north of Pula, and the [[D28 (Croatia)|D28]] spanning from the [[A4 (Croatia)|A4]] near Zagreb to [[Bjelovar]].&lt;ref name=&quot;HC-promet&quot;&gt;{{cite news | newspaper = [[Hrvatske ceste]] | url = http://www.hrvatske-ceste.hr/WEB%20-%20Legislativa/brojenje-prometa/CroDig2009.pdf | title = Traffic counting on the roadways of Croatia in 2009 - digest | accessdate = May 1, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Croatian motorway network is of very good overall quality and excellent safety, confirmed by several EuroTAP and EuroTest awards.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.eurotestmobility.com/news.php?item=25&amp;PHPSESSID=a7d9b4decd981bb3cdc3494656b0104d |title=EuroTest |publisher=Eurotestmobility.com |date= |accessdate=2009-01-03}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=38990 |title=Brinje Tunnel Best European Tunnel – Croatia – Javno |publisher=Javno.com |date= |accessdate=2009-01-03}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Marko Polo Rijeka 1 040408.jpg|thumb|[[Jadrolinija]]'s ship Marko Polo.]]

Croatia has an extensive rail network, although due to historical circumstances, some regions (notably [[Istria]] and even more so [[Dubrovnik]]) are not accessible by train without passing through neighboring countries. Serious investment is needed in the rail network over the coming decades to bring it up to European standards in both speed and operational efficiency. All rail services are operated by [[Croatian Railways]] ({{lang-hr|Hrvatske željeznice}}). The inter-city bus network (operated by private operators) is extensively developed, with higher levels of coverage and timetables than the railways.

Croatia has three major international airports, located in [[Zagreb Airport|Zagreb]], [[Split Airport|Split]] and [[Dubrovnik Airport|Dubrovnik]]. Other important airports include [[Zadar Airport|Zadar]], [[Rijeka Airport|Rijeka]] (on the island of [[Krk]]), [[Osijek Airport|Osijek]], [[Bol Airport|Bol]], [[Lošinj Airport|Lošinj]] and [[Pula Airport|Pula]]. [[Croatia Airlines]] is the national airline and [[flag carrier]]. The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) has assessed the Government of Croatia’s Civil Aviation Authority as being in compliance with International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) aviation safety standards for oversight of Croatia’s air carrier operations.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://travel.state.gov/travel/cis_pa_tw/cis/cis_1095.html |title=U.S. Department of State |publisher=Travel.state.gov |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt;

An extensive system of ferries, operated by [[Jadrolinija]], serves Croatia's many islands and links coastal cities. Ferry services to Italian cities of [[Venice]], [[Ancona]], [[Pescara]] and [[Bari]] from around a dozen of Croatian sea ports, most notably [[Rovinj]], [[Rijeka]], [[Zadar]], [[Split (city)|Split]], [[Korčula]] and [[Dubrovnik]], is available on a daily or weekly basis. From April to September the schedule is more dense and can include several round trips within a day.{{-}}

==Demographics==
{{Main|Demographics of Croatia}}
[[File:Hrvatske etnije.gif|thumb|180px|Ethnic map of Croatia.]]
[[File:St. Peter's Cathedral, Dakovo.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Historicism|Historicistic]] architecture of [[Đakovo Cathedral]].]]

{{bar box
|title=Religion in Croatia
|titlebar=#ddd
|left1=religion
|right1=percent
|float=left
|bars=
{{bar percent|[[Roman Catholicism]]|DarkGray|87.8}}
{{bar percent|[[Atheism]] or [[Agnosticism]]|MediumAquamarine|5.2}}
{{bar percent|[[Orthodox Church|Orthodoxy]]|Yellow|4.4}}
{{bar percent|[[Islam]]|Green|1.3}}
{{bar percent|Other or None|Lavender|0.9}}
{{bar percent|[[Protestantism]]|Orange|0.3}}
}}

Croatia's 2001 census recorded a total population of 4,437,460.&lt;ref name=&quot;frucht415&quot;/&gt; This is estimated to have risen to 4,489,409 by 2009.&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot;/&gt;

Croatia is inhabited mostly by [[Croats]] (89.6%), while minority groups include [[Serbs]] (4.5%), [[Bosniaks]], [[Hungarians]], [[Italians]], [[Slovenes]], [[Germans]], [[Czechs]], [[Romani people]] and others (5.9%).&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot; /&gt; For most of the 20th century, the population of Croatia has been rising from 3,430,270 in 1931 to 4,784,265 in 1991.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.vojska.net/eng/armed-forces/croatia/about/population/ |title=Vojska.net |publisher=Vojska.net |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; The natural growth rate of the population is currently negative&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot; /&gt; with the [[demographic transition]] completed in the 1970s.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last=Mrđen|first=Snježana|year=1998|title=The demographic situation in Croatia|journal=Geoadria|volume=3|pages=29–56|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/file/14991}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Average [[life expectancy]] is 75.1&amp;nbsp;years,&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot; /&gt; and the literacy rate is 98.1 percent.&lt;ref name=&quot;cia&quot; /&gt; During recent years, the Croatian government is pressured each year to add 40% to work permit quotas for foreign workers&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.poslovni.hr/101937.aspx |title=Traži se 40% više kvota za strane radnike |publisher=poslovni.hr |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; and in accordance with its immigration policy it is trying to entice emigrants to return.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ceeol.com/aspx/issuedetails.aspx?issueid=9f2dad2d-b334-433c-8887-d506b8d17eb7&amp;articleId=0d24a594-e1ec-4bda-945c-12e9c5d8313f |title=CEEOL Political Thought: Croatian Political Science Review , Issue 05 /1998 |publisher=Ceeol.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; The main religions of Croatia are Roman Catholic 88%, Orthodox 4.4%, other Christian 0.4%, Muslim 1.3%, other and unspecified 0.9%, none 5.2%.

During the last decade of the 20th century the population of Croatia has been stagnating because of the [[Croatian War of Independence]]. During the war, large sections of the population were displaced and emigration increased. In 1991, in predominantly Serb areas, more than 400 000 Croats and other non-Serbs were either removed out of their homes by the Croatian Serb forces or fled the violence.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/icty/pressreal/2007/pr1162e-summary.htm|title=Summary of judgement for Milan Martić|date=2007-06-12|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=2008-06-21 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071215084458/http://www.un.org/icty/pressreal/2007/pr1162e-summary.htm |archivedate = December 15, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; During the final days of the war in 1995, more than 120,000 Serbs,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E00EFD7113AF935A25752C0A9669C8B63 |title=For Serbs in Croatia, a Pledge Unkept |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=2000-01-16 | first=Steven | last=Erlanger | date=2000-01-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; and perhaps as many as 200,000&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last=Prodger |first=Matt |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/4747379.stm |title=Bbc News |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-08-05 |accessdate=2010-05-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; fled before the victory by Croatian forces.

Only a small fraction of Serbs have returned to their homes since 1995, according to [[Human Rights Watch]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hrea.org/lists/refugee-rights/markup/msg00610.html |title=refugee-rights@hrea.org – Croatia: Plight of returning Serb refugees may slow EU bid |publisher=Hrea.org |date= |accessdate=2009-01-03}}&lt;/ref&gt; Most of Croatia's remaining Serbs do not live in the highlands and inland of Dalmatia but rather in the Croatian heartland and major cities. Serbs have been only partially re-settled by the Croatian Government in the regions they previously inhabited (i.e., the blue areas of the map here). Many of the towns previously settled by Serbs were settled by Croat refugees from Bosnia and Herzegovina, mostly from [[Republika Srpska]].

===Education===
{{Main|Education in Croatia}}
[[File:University of Zagreb.jpg|thumb|The [[University of Zagreb]]]]

Primary education in Croatia starts at the age of six or seven and consists of eight grades. In 2007 a law was passed to increase free but not compulsory education until 18 years of age. Compulsory education consists of eight grades (Elementary School)
Secondary education is provided by [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasiums]] and [[vocational school]]s.

[[File:NSK Zagreb.jpg|thumb|left|[[National and University Library in Zagreb|University Library in Zagreb]]]]

Croatia has eight universities, the [[University of Zagreb]], [[University of Split]], [[University of Rijeka]], [[University of Osijek]], [[University of Zadar]], [[University of Dubrovnik]] the [[University of Pula]] and [[Dubrovnik International University]].
The [[University of Zadar]], the first University in Croatia, was founded in 1396 and remained active until 1807, when other institutions of higher education took over until the foundation of the renewed University of Zadar in 2002. The University of Zagreb, founded in 1669, is the oldest continuously operating University in [[Southeastern Europe]]. There are also 11 [[institute of technology|polytechnics]] and 23 [[higher education]] institutions of which 19 are private.

There are numerous public [[music school]]s on the primary and secondary education levels. Over thirty scientific [[institute]]s are registered in Croatia, the largest one being the [[Ruđer Bošković Institute|Institute &quot;Ruđer Bošković&quot;]] in Zagreb that excels in physics. The [[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] in Zagreb is a [[learned society]] promoting language, culture, arts and science from its first conception in 1836.

According to a survey ordered by the [[European commission]] in 2005, 49% of [[Croats]] speak [[english language|English]], 34% speak [[german language|German]], 14% [[italian language|Italian]], 4% [[French language|French]] and [[russian language|Russian]] and 2% [[spanish language|Spanish]] [[language]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_243_en.pdf|title=Europeans and their languages – European commission special barometer FEB2006|accessdate=2010-01-05}}&lt;/ref&gt;

A worldwide study about the quality of education in different countries published by [[Newsweek]] in August 2010 ranked Croatian education system on the 22nd place, to share the position with [[Austria]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2010/08/15/interactive-infographic-of-the-worlds-best-countries.html |title=Newsweek study of Health, Education, Economy and Politics ranks the globe's top nations |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=2010-08-15 |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Culture==
{{Main|Culture of Croatia}}
{{See also|Croatian art|Architecture of Croatia|Croatian literature|Croatian cuisine|Music of Croatia|Cinema of Croatia|Media in Croatia}}
[[File:Homar3 (js0.jpg|thumb|Mediterranian Cuisine in [[Dalmatia]]]]
[[File:Pula Amphitheater 2.JPG|thumb|Ancient Roman [[Pula Arena]]]]
[[File:Hrvatsko narodno kazaliste u Zagrebu 090609.jpg|thumb|[[Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb|National Theatre in Zagreb]]]]
{{Ref improve section|date=January 2011}}

Croatian culture is the result of a [[Culture of Croatia|fourteen century-long history]] which has seen the development of many cities and monuments and also includes many adoptions from ancient [[Ancient Greece|Greek]], [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] and [[Illyria]]n cultures. The culture of Croatia can be divided into two cultural circles: Central European and Mediterranean. The country includes [[Culture of Croatia#Places|seven World Heritage sites and eight national parks]]. Croatia is also the birthplace of a number of [[Culture of Croatia#People|historical figures]]. Included among the [[List of Croatians|notable people]] are three [[Nobel prize]] winners and numerous inventors. The country is also rich with [[Intangible culture]] and holds the largest number of [[Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity|UNESCO's World's intangible culture masterpieces]] in [[Europe]].

Regional cultures are considered variations on the larger category of &quot;Croatian&quot;, including the cultures of [[Dalmatia]], [[Istria]], [[Slavonia]], and [[Hrvatsko Zagorje|Zagorje]]. These regions are characterized by differences in geography, traditional economy, food, folkloric tradition, and dialect. Despite that, Croats share an overall sense of national culture but at the same time often feel strong about regional identities and about local cultural variations. Cultural variations, particularly regional cuisine, are related to geographic variations within the country. Traditional economies are also linked to geography. The capital, [[Zagreb]], is centrally located but was not chosen for that reason. It is the largest city, but also historically the political, commercial, and intellectual center.

Some of the world's first [[fountain pen]]s came from Croatia. Croatia also has a place in the history of clothing as the origin of the [[necktie]] (''kravata''). The country has a long [[Art of Croatia#Arts and literature|artistic, literary]] and [[Music of Croatia|musical tradition]]. Also of interest is the diverse nature of [[Croatian cuisine]] and the famous Croatian Traditional gift [[Licitar]].

Croatians are protective of the their [[Croatian language]] from foreign influences as the language was under constant change and threats imposed by previous rulers (i.e. Austrian German, Hungarian, Italian and Turkish words were changed and altered to &quot;Slavic&quot; looking/sounding ones).

The Croatian language has three major dialects, identified by three different words for &quot;what&quot; [[Chakavian dialect|ća]], [[Kajkavian dialect|kaj]] and [[Shtokavian dialect|što]]. From 1961 to 1991, the official language was Serbo-Croatian. Even under [[socialism]], Croats often referred to their language as Croato-Serbian (instead of Serbo-Croatian) or as Croatian. Croatian and Serbian variants of the language were never recognized as different, but referred as the west and east version, and had different alphabets; [[Latin alphabet]] and Serbian [[Cyrillic alphabet|Cyrillic]].

In the late 19th and 20th century, Serbian and Yugoslav nationalist scholars began to impose policies to change or alter Croatian words into &quot;Serbian&quot; or &quot;South Slavic&quot; ones, which have infuriated Croats over the purity and preservation of their native language (See [[Croatian linguistic purism]]). Under the Habsburgs, [[Latin language|Latin]] was the official language of the Croatian government and [[Sabor]]. At the same time, besides Croatian, many Croats used German and Italian in everyday life. A [[Illyrian movement|national reawakening]] in the 19th century focused on the establishment of a national language as the official one.

During socialist Yugoslavia, a Yugoslav identity was promoted and symbols and expressions of national identity were suppressed and punishable by jail terms. The [[Croatian Spring]], the most notable and only large-scale nationalist movement during Tito's regime, was put down in 1971 with most of its leadership imprisoned. It was led by important Croatian communists and was based on economic disagreement with the Serb elite in Belgrade.

[[File:Suit tie.JPG|thumb|left|[[Cravat]] or [[Necktie]] is a symbol of Croatian culture.]]

The newly independent state has had to recreate a national culture by drawing from history and folk culture. The modern national identity draws on its [[Kingdom of Croatia (medieval)|medieval roots]], association with Viennese &quot;high culture,&quot; culturally diverse rural traditions, and Roman Catholicism.

A [[cravat]] (in modern [[English language|English]] renamed to [[Necktie]]), symbol of culture and elegance, originates from the 17th century Croatia where it was part of the uniform worn by Croatian soldiers. It was disseminated across Europe during [[Thirty Years' War]] (1618–1648) by Croatian regiments serving under Austria. From 1635 Croatian soldiers also served in France and in 1667 a special regiment named Royal Cravates was formed. Common soldiers wore scarves made of coarse materials and officers wore scarves made of fine cotton or silk. French King [[Louis XIV]] fell in love with the Croatian attire and soon replaced the starched high-lace collar the French used to wear with the cravat, much more practical and beautiful piece of clothing. When the most powerful European king put on the cravat, a new fashion was born. Later on, cravat was accepted in all corners of the world as a standard and still carries the Croatian name in its name in majority of modern languages.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://academia-cravatica.hr/etimology/ |title=Academia Cravatica |publisher=Academia-cravatica.hr |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{-}}

===Architecture===
{{Main|Architecture of Croatia}}
{{See also|World Heritage Sites in Croatia}}

Architecture in Croatia reflects the influence of the bordering nations. Austrian and Hungarian influences are visible in public space and buildings in the north and central regions. Large squares named for culture heroes, well-groomed parks, and pedestrian-only zones, are features of these orderly towns and cities. Muted colors prevail, especially tones of yellow and gold. In urban areas, houses are built right up to the street. An inner courtyard sometimes provides space for a small garden. Modern houses in cities and villages usually have two or three stories with [[masonry]] and [[stucco]].

Along the coast, the architecture is Mediterranean. Houses are usually made of stucco and painted white, and have red tile roofs. Cities and towns still have the characteristic open markets, squares, and Catholic churches, but are less likely to be laid out in a neat grid. Generally speaking, continental architecture is of [[baroque architecture]] gauge and coastal areas are examples of [[renaissance architecture]].

[[File:SplitM1.jpg|thumb|[[Split (city)|Split]]]]

World heritage sites in Croatia include:

* Historical Complex of [[Split (city)|Split]] with the [[Diocletian's Palace|Palace of Diocletian]] (1979)
* Old City of [[Dubrovnik]] (1979)
* [[Plitvice Lakes]] National Park (1979)
* Episcopal Complex of the [[Euphrasian Basilica]] in the Historic Centre of [[Poreč]] (1997)
* Historic City of [[Trogir]] (1997)
* The [[Cathedral of St. James, Šibenik|Cathedral of St. James]] in [[Šibenik]] (2000)
* The [[Stari Grad Plain]] – island of [[Hvar]] (2008)

===Sport===
{{Main|Sport in Croatia}}
[[File:Hns-dres.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Croatian [[checkerboard]] from the Coat of Arms is used as the colour of national teams and athletes from the country.]]
{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2011}}

The most popular sports in Croatia are [[association football|football]], [[team handball|handball]], [[basketball]], [[water polo]], [[tennis]], and [[skiing]].

The [[Croatian national football team]] won a bronze medal in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Davor Šuker]] won the [[FIFA World Cup awards|Golden Boot]] as the top goal scorer. The national football team has also played in the quarter-finals of the [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996 European Championships]] and the [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 European Championships]]. The team is currently ranked 8th in the [[FIFA World Rankings]] (as of March 2011). The most popular football players are [[Luka Modrić]], [[Darijo Srna]], [[Ivica Olić]], [[Niko Kranjcar]].

[[File:Ivano Balic.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ivano Balić]], [[team handball|handball]] player&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ihf.info/MediaCenter/News/NewsDetails/tabid/130/Default.aspx?ID=418 |title=International Handball Federation |publisher=Ihf.info |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;]]
[[File:JanicaKostelic.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Janica Kostelić]], the best [[Alpine skiing|alpine ski racer]] of all time. Won four [[Alpine skiing at the Winter Olympics|Winter Olympic]] and five [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|FIS Championship]] gold medals.]]
[[File:Blanka Vlasic.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Blanka Vlašić]], European and World [[high jump]] champion and current European athlete of the year&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.european-athletics.org/european-athletics-awards-night/croatias-vlai-voted-2010-european-athlete-of-the-year.html |title=European athletics association |publisher=European-athletics.org |date= |accessdate=2010-11-14}}&lt;/ref&gt;]]

The [[Croatia national handball team]] is a two-time Olympic Champion ([[Handball at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]] and [[Handball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004]]). The team also won a gold medal at the [[2003 World Men's Handball Championship]], and silver medals in the [[1995 World Men's Handball Championship|1995]], [[2003 World Men's Handball Championship|2003]] and [[2009 World Men's Handball Championship|2009]] World Championships. Croatia won bronze medal in [[1994 European Men's Handball Championship|1994 European Championships]] and silver in [[2008 European Men's Handball Championship|2008]]. [[RK Zagreb]] was a 1992 and 1993 [[EHF Champions League|European champion]] and 4 times a runner-up (1995, 1997, 1998 and 1999). Croatian players [[Ivano Balić]], [[Igor Vori]] and [[Domagoj Duvnjak]] are currently among the best handball players in the world.

The [[Croatian national basketball team]] won a silver medal at the [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic basketball tournament]], bronze medal at the [[1994 FIBA World Championship]] and bronze medals at [[EuroBasket 1993]] and [[EuroBasket 1995]]. Croatian basketball clubs were [[Euroleague]] champions 5 times: [[KK Split]] three times (in 1989, 1990 and 1991) and [[KK Cibona]] in 1985 and 1986. Croatian basketball players such as [[Dražen Petrović]], [[Krešimir Ćosić]] and [[Toni Kukoč]] were amongst the first foreign players to succeed in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] in the [[United States]].

The [[Croatia national water polo team]] won a gold medal at the [[Water Polo at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 FINA World Championships]] and bronze medal in [[Water polo at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships – Men's tournament|2009]]. The team also won a silver medal at the [[Water Polo at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympic water polo tournament]] and gold medal at the [[2010 Men's European Water Polo Championship|2010 European Championship]] as well as silver medals in the 1999 and 2003 European Championships. Croatian water polo clubs were 13 times [[LEN Euroleague]] champions. [[HAVK Mladost]] from Zagreb was a seven time European Champion (in 1968, 1969, 1970, 1972, 1990, 1991 and 1996) and was awarded the title ''Best Club of the 20th Century'' by the [[Ligue européenne de natation|LEN]]. [[VK Jug]] from Dubrovnik and [[VK Jadran]] from Split were both three time European champions.

The [[Croatia Davis Cup team|Croatian Davis Cup team]] ([[Ivan Ljubičić]], [[Mario Ančić]] and [[Ivo Karlović]] with coach [[Nikola Pilić]]) won the [[2005 Davis Cup]] tournament and reached semifinals in [[2009 Davis Cup|2009]] tournament ([[Marin Čilić]] and Ivo Karlović with coach [[Goran Prpić]]). [[Goran Ivanišević]] is one of the country's most popular sportsmen. Ivanišević won the [[2001 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|2001 Wimbledon Men's singles]] title and reached number 2 spot in [[ATP Rankings]] in July 1994. Ivan Ljubičić reached number 3 spot in ATP Rankings in May 2006. [[Iva Majoli]] won the [[1997 French Open – Women's Singles|1997 Roland Garros Women's Singles]] title. Currently the best Croatian tennis player is Marin Čilić ranked 14th as of November 16, 2009.

[[Janica Kostelić]] is the most successful female [[Alpine skiing|alpine ski racer]] in the history of the [[Winter Olympic Games]]. She is the only woman to win four gold medals in alpine skiing at the [[Alpine skiing at the Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics Alpine skiing events]] (in [[Alpine skiing at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002]] and [[Alpine skiing at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006]]), and the only woman to win three alpine skiing gold medals in one Olympics ([[Alpine skiing at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002]]). She also won two slilver medals in [[Alpine skiing at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006]]. Janica was the [[Alpine Skiing World Cup|World Cup]] overall champion in [[2001 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2001]], [[Alpine Skiing World Cup|2003]], and [[Alpine Skiing World Cup|2006]]. On February 5, 2006 Janica became only the second female skier to win all five disciplines in one season. She also holds the record for the highest number of points in one World Cup season. In 2006 she won [[Laureus World Sports Award for Sportswoman of the Year]]. Her elder brother [[Ivica Kostelić]] was the [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2003|2003 World Champion in slalom]] and is a three-time Winter Olympic silver medalist himself.

[[Blanka Vlašić]] is the best-known Croatian [[track and field athletics|track and field athlete]]; she specialises in the [[high jump]]. She is [[2007 World Championships in Athletics – Women's high jump|2007]] and [[2009 World Championships in Athletics – Women's high jump|2009 World Champion]]. Blanka is also [[2008 IAAF World Indoor Championships - Women's High Jump|2008 World Indoor Champion]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's high jump|2008 Olympic silver medalist]]. Her personal best is {{convert|2.08|m|2|abbr=on|lk=out}} (which is only 1&amp;nbsp;cm less than the world record) set in Zagreb at August 31, 2009.

Biathlete [[Jakov Fak]] won bronze medal in [[Biathlon World Championships 2009#Men|World Championships 2009]] in [[Pyeongchang]] and another bronze medal in [[Biathlon at the 2010 Winter Olympics#Men's events|2010 Winter Olympics]] in [[Vancouver]]. Before Fak Croatia had no success or tradition in [[biathlon]].

[[Croatia women's national volleyball team]] won silver medals three times at [[European Volleyball Championship]] in [[1995 Women's European Volleyball Championship|1995]], [[1997 Women's European Volleyball Championship|1997]] and [[1999 Women's European Volleyball Championship|1999]].

Other well-known Croatian athletes are [[Duje Draganja]], [[Gordan Kožulj]], [[Sanja Jovanović]] and [[Đurđica Bjedov]] in [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[Zoran Primorac]], [[Dragutin Šurbek]], [[Antun Stipančić]] and [[Tamara Boroš]] in [[table tennis]], [[Filip Ude]] in [[gymnastics]], [[Siniša Skelin|Siniša]] and [[Nikša Skelin]] in [[rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[Martina Zubčić]] and [[Sandra Šarić]] in [[taekwondo]], [[Snježana Pejčić]] in [[shooting]], [[Matija Ljubek]] in [[canoeing]], [[Željko Mavrović]] and [[Mate Parlov]] in [[boxing]], and [[Branko Cikatić]] and [[Mirko Filipović|Mirko &quot;Cro Cop&quot; Filipović]] in [[kickboxing]].

